Route 53 health checks and hybrid D-N-S.

Route 53's health checkers are a fleet on the public internet that probe an endpoint from many locations and decide healthy or unhealthy by majority; typically about three of eighteen-plus probers must agree before the status flips. There are three flavours. Endpoint is a direct H-T-T-P, H-T-T-P-S, or T-C-P probe on a path you specify, passing on a two-hundred or three-hundred response within four seconds, with optional string matching on the first five kilobytes of the body, which is useful when a broken app still returns a two hundred. Calculated is a logical A-N-D, O-R, or N-O-T of other health checks, for when "up" depends on several parts. And CloudWatch alarm reads health off an alarm; this is the only way to check a private resource, because the probers are on the public internet and can't reach private I-Ps. The pattern is: emit a metric, set an alarm, and point the health check at it.

Health checks feed the routing policies: failover, weighted, latency, and multivalue all drop unhealthy records automatically.

For hybrid D-N-S, every V-P-C has the built-in Route 53 Resolver at base-plus-two. Two endpoint types bridge to on-premises. An inbound endpoint lets on-prem servers resolve names in a private hosted zone; that's on-prem to AWS. An outbound endpoint, working with Resolver Rules, forwards queries for, say, corp-dot-internal to your on-prem D-N-S server; that's AWS to on-prem. Each endpoint is a set of E-N-Is, one per availability zone for high availability, and Resolver Rules can be shared across accounts via Resource Access Manager.
